segments.text: Describe a football weekend.
When did the activities begin and take me through a weekend?
Well, for those of us that didn't have dates, and most of the time we didn't, you know, the same four of us used to go to the ball games.
We'd sit, you know, wherever.
But did you go to anything on Friday night?
We always had midnight yell practice.
Describe midnight yell practice.
Where did it occur?
At the Grove.

We went to the Grove on Midnight Yale practice, and we already were, we would stay around Friday night, and even as upperclassmen, there weren't a whole lot of places to go and do, unless you went to a movie or the legal drinking age of 21, and so, you know, we didn't, there wasn't the, I guess Uncle Ed's was there and a couple other places, but number one, we didn't have the money to go do that.
Did, all right, at the Grove, did y'all do the yells and the songs, and were there fables?
Absolutely.
And the moments when someone was speaking, I remember when Bear Bryant spoke at one.
I remember when other, of course the Yell leaders would always carry it, but I guess the one I remember the most was when Bear Bryant spoke.
But that was, of course we also had during the week, if it was a away game on Tuesday and Thursday night after mess hall,
After dinner, we would go to the Grove and have a Yale practice on Tuesday and Thursday during football season.
Right after summer?
Right after summer.
And then, of course, but not when it was a home game.
We didn't go on Thursday, which ended in a Yale practice.
And we would, you know, line up at the, arm and arm to the Grove and the band, I guess the band led it.
I could be confused with what I see today, but I'm sure they did.
Yeah, of course, they had to.
We had all the songs, the normal songs that we sang and everything else.
So they were sometimes, of course, you've got to make people yell.
And I guess they made us yell to break the shyness of yelling like freshmen and posture.
You learn that at football games, too.
But that's just for the first two or three, and then pretty much leave it alone.
And once you get it and do it right, nobody knows.
Were there any Korean War veterans that you remember much?
There were a lot of veterans, because the student body was about half Corps, of the 7,000 plus, 7,500, 3,500.
strength core.
My brother was back.
See, Gus returned to A&M mid-semester of my freshman year.
And he and I went to college together, even though he was my older brother.
Because when, see he was 15 when he graduated from high school.
And then he went to A&M.
My dad didn't let him go off until
He stayed at Loretta Junior College for either a year or a semester, I can't remember.
Probably a semester.
And then when he was 16, he went up in Frog Den.
And he was, I guess, immature.
And they asked him to go home and grow up a little bit, and he joined the Air Force.
And after four years in the Air Force, he got out right at my first semester freshman, and he came back in.
I saw a lot of the veterans because my brother was a veteran.
He wasn't a Korean veteran, but he was a veteran.
And they were mainly quiet.
They screwed the curves up because they were serious about studying.
Where did they live?
Puryear and Law and the non-core dorms.
They were also in one of the, let me see, it was 14, 15, 16, and 18.
Were you all aware of many married veterans, many married students?
They were, and they were in the apartments that were in... College View?
Yeah, College View.
There's one over here and one over there.
And the project house is down south.
Yeah, two different places.
And there were a lot of married students.
And they were serious students, and they pretty much... What school?
Describe...
your routine in going to and from home to College Station?
How'd you get there?
Well, once Gus was there, when we went home, Gus had a car.
So hitchhiking days were over.
Describe hitchhiking, though.
Hitchhiking?
Well, the line, you know, you go, even though... Now where was the place, if you're coming in this direction?
Where did you get the...
The road that runs out through North, what is that?
Yeah, but you have to go 50-60 or 60-50.
I never could remember.
Across the railroad tracks right there, across the tracks on the street that runs in front of the... You're talking about the Wellburn Road?
North Gate.
All right.
Okay.
Going towards 21.
Okay.
And that's where the line was there.
Of course, there was a line on...
going to Houston or going to Dallas, but I didn't have to hitchhike a whole lot.
We normally, there were a few people from the radio that had cars, and then of course once dusk got there, the only time I went home was either Thanksgiving or Easter or something like that.
Did you ever have any bad experiences hitchhiking?
Well, I finished high school.
I hitchhiked to Chicago and worked that summer.
I worked two jobs.
You and I would be petrified if one of our children or grandchildren wanted to do that.
I turned 18 on the 17th of June, and on the 18th I hitchhiked to Chicago.
That's where I got the money to go the first semester without work.
He's Dr. Alabama.
Sylvia was a student there.
She was a student there my junior and senior, no, sophomore freshman.
See, she finished high school a year after I did and finished college a year before I did.
Great.
Now, she's from Laredo?
Yes.
Right.
How did you all maintain contact?
Letter writing.
Letter writing.
Every day.
Every day.
Both directions?
Yeah.
Do you remember, did she come to A&M for any important events?
Yes, she did.
A football game when I was a freshman.
She enjoyed the TCU tornado, or hurricane, whatever it was that went through there.
And she had new clothes on and new shoes, and we just totally danced.
That was as a freshman.
She came for my junior year, came to combat ball.
From Alabama.
How did she get there?
By train.
From Loretta, though, when she was a high school senior, friends that were going up there, friends of her family.
Her mother wouldn't let her go.
She came from Alabama by train.
Where did you meet the train?
Good question.
Was it up in Iola, or was it there on the West Gate at the college station?
Well, it must not have been a terribly difficult time.
It must have been easy for her.
Where did she stay?
She stayed with Tommy and Carolyn Lumpen when she came as a junior.
And when she came out of the freshman, she only came twice.
When she came out of freshman, she had a cousin that lived there.
It was, again, in the apartments.
Now, you all didn't, by chance, get engaged or anything on an A&M weekend?
No.
OK. See, I was going to ask you to describe what you could if that had happened.
Let's see, did you take her to any boot dance or?
I took her to the combat ball when I was a freshman.
I mean, excuse me, a junior.
Describe that weekend, please.
Because a lot of activities and it was a show off your girlfriends kind of a thing.
And by that time, a lot of our classmates had their girlfriends there.
And that's when we first started making some of the friends that we still have.
Where did she stay?
She stayed with Tommy again.
And what did one wear to the combat ball?
You want to see a picture?
I've got one.
No, just describe it.
Well, see, the combat ball, we wore fatigues, and we got fatigued kind of dressed for our dates.
But in the military ball, they dress up in nice, we wore the...
or better uniforms, and then they wore the lacy, I don't know how many undercoats, petticoats kind of thing.
Where were those dances held?
Sedesa.
And was there a particular band that played?
Aggie Network.
Okay.
And how did people behave themselves at those?
Very well.
It was, they were fun occasions.
And people got there on time, and
You know, maybe left towards the end of it, but it was an event.
Let's see.
You didn't have a car.
When Gus was there, I had a useful car.
You had a useful car, but you didn't know him, right?
He finished, I was, the fifth year I was there, Gus graduated that, when I should have, in 59, and then I finished in 60.
And I'll take it back to you, but Gus finished in 58.
And...
So I didn't have a car the last two years.
Let's see.
The president, when you were there, was there?
That's a guy that impressed me.
Huh?
Earl Rutter.
OK.
Describe Earl Rutter.
OK. See, he was a charger.
He was a charger.
It was his first year.
Because he came there.
He was brought there.
I think being groomed, as I now understand, being groomed for president.
My roommate, John Thomas, and his daddy and Earl Rudder were at Tarleton together.
And of course, we were the General Moore outfit our senior year.
We had the Corps.
And so we got to see him a lot.
Because any visitors that came, he would bring them over to our house.
And he would go through our place.
And he was just a dynamic.
I didn't know him, I saw him a lot, but we didn't have the relationship, maybe some did, I did not, with the President, like students do today.
They probably were, I just wasn't one of them.
Did you all think that he was in charge?
You didn't have to think that, he let you know.
But I wish, talking about
And I had the beautiful good luck of being, working in the A&M clubs after I came back from the service and got to be around him a little bit in that capacity.
But I'll never forget, we had our 10-year reunion in 69, right before he died.
He came to our reunion.
And he and his brother.
And he went up to the podium to speak.
He takes off his jacket, his coat, he takes off his tie, and he rolls his sleeves up.
And I wish I had a recording of that of what he, the talk that he was capable of inspiring people.
He was, he was certainly, you know, a motivation to us.
Let's see, other...
campus individuals.
Lupo?
Did you ever deal with Lupo?
We went in the store.
Everybody knew Lupo, and Lupo knew you whether he did or not.
I didn't spend that much money in the store.
I did buy books and stuff there.
I knew him, but I never... You didn't borrow money from him?
No.
Because a lot of students did.
What about Pinky?
We saw Pinky.
Pinky was up, you know, later.
He was already later in years.
What was his function?
I don't think he had an official function other than being the campus greeter.
He was just there.
Pinky was there.
I don't believe he had an official function.
Describe the community, the neighborhood around A&M.
What was at the North Gate?
Lupo's, and there was a pool hall up there on top of the corner drug store.
We didn't have time to play pool either.
of course they had a theater over there.
Did y'all go often?
A little bit, not that often, not that often.
Of course the boot shop was there, and there were a couple of other... Where'd you buy your boots?
I bought them from a Greek friend of Paul Boinus', who lived in Houston, and those boots in 58, 59 were probably already
25, 30 years old.
Did you sell them?
Do you remember what you paid for them?
Probably around $50.
And you didn't pass them on?
No, I kept them upstairs.
Because there are some people that have done both, haven't they?
Some keep them and some pass them on?
Pass them on.
They were an older boot.
They were probably a little uncomfortable.
I have a narrow foot.
They did fit.
But at that time, for some reason, we were dumb, it was, it was, you were considered too core happy to wear your boots too much.
Where was Uncle Ed's?
Uncle Ed's was out on the... Welborn Road?
By the railroad?
I thought it was out the other direction.
I don't know.
Towards Whiskey Bridge.
Okay.
Isn't that where it was?
I don't know.
It was on this side of the river.
It was in Brazos County.
I know we used to drive over to the other side of the river to buy anything.
That was to buy whiskey.
Uncle Ed used to beer.
That's what I thought.
Did you know of any place in Brazos County where anybody could have bought whiskey?
Was there any bootlegger?
No.
I've not heard of one.
Were you all aware of any house of ill repute in Brazos County?
I've not heard of one.
No.
All right.
During your day, what were the people drank what?
What alcohol?
Beer and whiskey?
Beer, maybe.
I guess if anybody was able to get a hold of whiskey, you'd see some of that.
Do you remember any stunts or anything of anybody having beer or whiskey in their rooms?
No.
Beer didn't last long when we got it, but I don't remember in our rooms.
So you don't remember anybody smuggling anybody back to the door?
Beer or body.
No, no.
Beer or whiskey.
No.
I imagine there was some.
Maybe the seniors who were of age.
We didn't.
I'm not trying to sound pure.
No, no.
I hear you.
Let's see.
Do you remember any special off-campus national or international events that kind of caught your attention?
No.
See, there wasn't a Kennedy
No, Kennedy assassination is later.
The Korean War is over.
Eisenhower came before that.
I remember in 1959 we had Aggie Muster on the grass in front of the MSE and Congressman Teague
was a speaker.
And he talked about the space program.
He talked about the importance of technology, where we were going as a country.
And it was all Star Wars to us at the time.
But he said what was going to happen.
And it did happen.
And he helped make a lot of it happen.
All right, let's go back to Muster.
Where was it held?
As far as you recall, was it always held at the system building?
The other three years, up to my senior year, if I recall, it was in front of the system building.
As a senior, we held it in front of the NSC.
Oh, in front of the NSC.
And generally, the people who attended Muster were?
Students.
Students.
At that time, yeah.
Not many off-campus.
As you heard the roll call, did that do anything to your sensitivities, your emotions?
Those were the students that had passed away during that year.
The same honored as Silver Taps.
And Silver Taps was always a very emotional ceremony.
Why emotional?
Well, I guess
We gave a lot of importance because I guess it was important that we lost a classmate or an Aggie.
There weren't as many deaths, probably, as there are now.
They're just sheer numbers.
But it was such a solid thing.
The campus was more organized and controlled, whatever you want to call it.
And when the lights went out on the campus, they went out.
I mean, the campus was in total darkness.
So we all didn't
Y'all didn't play any pranks?
No, no, absolutely not.
Absolutely not.
It was serious.
Nobody spoke, nobody talked.
So I went back to your room.
If you did have to study, you covered, you put blankets up, and it remained dark.
But it was very, very solid.
We'll look on the other side of the page now.
In terms of student excesses, people smoked what?
Cigarettes.
It was a junior privilege to smoke a pipe, so we tried that.
Didn't like it either.
Did you all know about any other substances?
Never saw anything else smoked.
Did you even know the term, the words?
You know, I grew up in Laredo, and I never saw one there.
I mean, you heard about it, you knew about it, but in that time marijuana was a... You heard of what?
Marijuana.
Okay, did you even know the word cocaine?
No.
I would have been surprised if you had said yes.
Anything else?
Speed or anything else?
No, no.
It was a simpler era than today.
Let's see.
Final review your junior and senior year.
Okay.
We got screwed out of our last, when the seniors, it rained, it rained so hard we didn't have final review when we were seniors.
Well, as juniors,
That was in, that was May of 58.
That was really special because, you see, Gus graduated that weekend.
Sylvia came up.
Albert and Mary, my brother Albert, he was, he was married.
Mary came up.
I'm trying to think if Gus was already dating his wife-to-be.
I think my mother came up to that too.
No, I don't think she did.
She came up to my graduation.
How serious were you and Sylvia then?
We'd been going together since I was a senior in high school and she was a junior in high school.
So we'd been going together for a long time.
So it's pretty special.
I didn't know that one was ever made out.
And it was held on the drill field where they are today.
Right now, let's do commencement.
Where were, describe commencement and your feelings about it.
Exciting.
You know, I guess I was, it was more than just commencement.
It was, even though
See, I graduated in May of 60, and well, a lot of my class was still there, okay?
In fact, Wesley and Mike, and you see, Williams finished in four and a half years, but Wesley, Mike, and I, we were real close.
We always worked together.
We all finished in May of 60, and so we donned our uniforms, and of course, we had commissioning that afternoon, but...
they're still the emotional, beautiful exercise that still goes on today.
Was either a speaker, either commissioning, or commencement, was there anybody that was unusual?
You know, I'm not proud of myself for not remembering, because I've been to, as you well know, a zillion graduations.
school district here in San Antonio where I served and then the A&M system.
But you would have remembered if it had been a governor or a president, so you're telling me.
I don't know.
I was so excited and so, you know, it may have been a person of great importance and I don't remember.
I should ask when I'm off and when I'm talking at
okay just a few more minutes and we're down to serious what are the factors events or whatever that contributes to Aggie spirit
What makes that?
Everything around the Aggie spirit, with me, revolved around the Corps of Cadets, because that's where we learned it.
That's where we felt it.
I think one of the most important happenings as a freshman, and I have a theory about that, is that first march in.
You can keep a freshman to that first march in, and you feel your heart pounding.
going around that track, and you feel the beat.
And I've seen years when we don't have the ball game early, we have a lot of freshmen in the quarter loss.
But that was an important event as far as feeling something.
All right.
What are the other events that help build that feeling that go to it?
Whenever one works with a group, and we were a group as a unit, we had our special group in our class.
I've never had a lot of other experiences like that where everybody gives something and be part of a group or a unit or an effort or something with a supposedly positive
And, or means, even war is a, I've not been in a war.
I'm not, you know, I served in the military, and I felt that Supreme Court there, too.
It has to do with that, I think, of belonging to something that at the time is important.
As you were getting ready to leave the campus as a graduate, did you have any feelings about whether or not you were prepared for the real world?
Did you feel?
I would have to say I probably didn't feel as prepared as I do today from the standpoint of just not feeling unprepared.
I was confident I could speak and I could
do a lot of the things that people have to know how to do to get along professionally.
But, you know, there's always that question.
And then, see, I graduated on a Saturday morning, a commission Saturday afternoon.
I went to work Monday morning, break with Zachary Kimberley.
And I was troubled.
I didn't enjoy that year.
I didn't enjoy it at all.
And I went to work for the service.
It was like playing again.
And to me, work is play.
If it's not play, I don't want to do it.
And I almost stayed in the Army.
I came so close to in the Army.
But the factor there was, and I guess I learned that at A&M, saying thank you and not being afraid to talk to somebody.
I met Mr. Zachary while I was working at the company.
And when I left the company, right before I was scheduled to leave and report to service, I went to his office in the office of transit tower building.
and knocked on his door and asked to see him and went and thanked him.
It wasn't his fault I didn't enjoy it.
And he said, well, Raul, when you come back, you come see me.
And to me, I said I had a job.
And so I came back and he sent me out to gym up more.
And small construction and development and get dirty kind of work.
And that's where I found what I was supposed to be doing.
As you look back on it, did A&M prepare you pretty well for that?
Oh, no question.
Even, you know, I never really used engineering as much as, say, my brothers did.
or as much as some of my other colleagues, because I, you know, past it active, I was maybe more, even though it's not an inactive profession, but it wasn't what I needed to be doing.
But I worked with engineering all the time, because I worked with engineers, with architects, worked with all the same kinds of things that we were prepared for and doing.
I certainly have the
the confidence skills.
I learned, you know, I learned, I listened, and I led while I was at A&M.
And then that taught me to lead, because you come right back in as a freshman again, and you woke up.
So that's the other education that we talk about and John told us to express so well.
other education or learning or learning laboratory or leadership.
All right now this is one question but I may ask it three or four different ways.
What difference did it make in your life that you attended A&M?
What did being an Aggie what what is all that what did it mean to you?
Well maybe I would have been a service
oriented kind of a person anyway.
I don't know.
But I think we were instilled in us the service to others.
And frankly, that other education probably served me better over the years than the technical education that I got, even though we
We couldn't be in one place without the other.
And they both get you there.
But unfortunately, or fortunately, whatever one wants to put it, everybody ends up with people and with opportunities to make something happen.
And working with people, working with yourself
handling that made a lot of difference in my life.
And if I hadn't have gone to A&M, I probably wouldn't have gotten a job with A.P.
Zachary Hemsworth.
If I hadn't have gone to talk to Mr. Zachary and say thank you, I wouldn't have gotten
